Introduction to the Differential Algebra Normal Form Algorithm using the Centrifugal Governor as an Example

Adrian Weisskopf111Michigan State University - Department of Physics and Astronomy â€” weisskop@msu.edu
Abstract

This paper provides a detailed introduction into the differential algebra (DA) based normal form algorithm using the example of the symplectic one dimensional system of the centrifugal governor. The intention of this paper is to make the single steps of the algorithm as clear as possible in the hope that the understanding and use of DA normal form methods are spread throughout the scientific community.

1 Introduction

This paper provides an example-driven walk-through of the differential algebra (DA) based normal form algorithm for a symplectic one dimensional (1D) system.

The DA framework was first developed to its current extent by Berz et al. [3, 1, 2]. It allows for an analytic/numeric-hybrid representation and manipulation of analytic functions in form of polynomial expansions. Taylor polynomials of order mğ‘šm are represented by DA vectors which store the coefficients of the individual terms with floating point accuracy together with the order of the corresponding variables. Operations are defined on the DA vectors and implemented in the framework.

The DA normal form algorithm [3] is an advancement from the DA-Lie based version, the first arbitrary order algorithm by Forest, Berz, and Irwin [5]. The DA normal form algorithm yields a nonlinear change of phase space variables by an order-by-order transformation that significantly simplifies the representation to be rotational invariant up to the order of calculation. Thus, the resulting normal form representation, up to the order of calculation, constitutes circular motion with quasi-invariants as radii and only normal form phase space amplitude (and parameter) dependent angle advancements (see Fig. 1a+b).

The explanations on the DA normal form algorithm in this paper are based on Ref. [3], which also contains details on the calculation of the DA normal form algorithm for higher dimensional systems and other various special cases like non-symplectic systems. The appendix 5 yields a short summary on the main changes when considering higher dimensional phase space systems, e.g. resonances etc.

We start with an introduction to the centrifugal governor and the derivation of the equations of motion. This is followed by the calculation of an approximation of the flow of the equations of motions around an equilibrium position/point. This approximated flow is referred to as fixed point map. Given a linearly stable fixed point map, we go through the DA normal form algorithm step by step to obtain the rotationally invariant normal form map. The normal form is calculated up to third order. It will become obvious during the example that transformations of higher even and odd orders follow the same procedure as the second and third order transformation, respectively.

2 The centrifugal governor

The centrifugal governor is a device involving gravitational and centrifugal forces with the rotation axis parallel to the direction of the gravitational force. We are considering a mathematically idealized governor, which consists of two massless rods of equal length Rğ‘…R suspended at opposite sides of the rotation axis and a point mass mğ‘šm attached at the end (opposite to where the rod is mounted) of each of the rods (see Fig. 1c). The angle between the rotation axis (in direction of gravitational pull) and the rod is denoted with the angle Ï•italic-Ï•\phi.

At a sufficiently high rotation frequency Ï‰>Ï‰mâ€‹iâ€‹nğœ”subscriptğœ”ğ‘šğ‘–ğ‘›\omega>\omega_{min} (see eq. 1) the centrifugal force Fcâ€‹eâ€‹nâ€‹tsubscriptğ¹ğ‘ğ‘’ğ‘›ğ‘¡F_{cent} carries the masses radially outward, while the gravitational force Fgâ€‹râ€‹aâ€‹vsubscriptğ¹ğ‘”ğ‘Ÿğ‘ğ‘£F_{grav} pulls down on them. The tension Tğ‘‡T in the rods is given by the vector sum of the two forces. For every rotation frequency Ï‰>Ï‰mâ€‹iâ€‹nğœ”subscriptğœ”ğ‘šğ‘–ğ‘›\omega>\omega_{min}, there is an equilibrium angle Ï•0>0subscriptitalic-Ï•00\phi_{0}>0 (see subsection 2.1) where the gravitational and centrifugal forces balance.

A centrifugal governor is usually used in the application of a self-regulating mechanism, where the angle Ï•italic-Ï•\phi is negatively coupled back to the rotation frequency Ï‰ğœ”\omega through an extra mechanism (increase in Ï•italic-Ï•\phi â‡’â‡’\Rightarrow decrease in Ï‰ğœ”\omega). Accordingly, in those applications, e.g. the steam engine, the rotation frequency Ï‰ğœ”\omega changes during the regulating process.

For the introduction to the normal form algorithm, we are considering the motion of the system with a fixed externally driven rotation frequency Ï‰ğœ”\omega. In particular, we are interested in the motion around the equilibrium position/angle Ï•0â€‹(Ï‰)subscriptitalic-Ï•0ğœ”\phi_{0}\left(\omega\right) for a specific rotation frequency Ï‰ğœ”\omega. If the rods are perturbed from their equilibrium position/angle Ï•0â€‹(Ï‰)subscriptitalic-Ï•0ğœ”\phi_{0}\left(\omega\right), they oscillate around Ï•0â€‹(Ï‰)subscriptitalic-Ï•0ğœ”\phi_{0}\left(\omega\right) and we what to study the dynamics of that motion using the DA normal form algorithm.
